On the evening of 19 December 2016, a [[car ramming attack|truck was driven into]] the [[Christmas market]] next to the [[Kaiser Wilhelm Memorial Church]] at [[Breitscheidplatz]] in [[Berlin]]. 12 people were killed and 56 others injured. One of the victims was the truck's original driver, Łukasz Urban, who was found shot dead in the passenger seat. A suspect was arrested and later released due to lack of evidence. Another person suspected to be the actual perpetrator was killed four days later during a shootout with police near [[Milan]] in Italy. 

Police and the [[Prosecutors Office|public prosecutor]] are treating the attack as [[Terrorism in Germany|terrorism]]. The [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] claimed responsibility for the attack,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ict.org.il/Article/1883/the-berlin-vehicular-ramming-attack|title=The Berlin Vehicular Ramming Attack – What we know & Insights from ICT Experts|website=www.ict.org.il|access-date=2016-12-22}}</ref> saying the attacker answered its calls to target the citizens of [[Military intervention against ISIL|states that are fighting against it]].<ref name="bbc isis claim">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-38385961 "Berlin attack: So-called Islamic State claims responsibility"]. [[BBC News]]. 20 December 2016. Retrieved 21 December 2016.</ref>

==Background==
The attack took place during a time of [[Wave of Terror in Europe|heightened Islamist terrorist activity in Europe]]. Several terrorist attacks in 2016, in Germany and in neighboring countries, have been linked to the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL);<ref name="bbcbackground">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36882445 "Germany attacks: What is going on?"]. [[BBC News]]. 20 December 2016. Retrieved 21 December 2016.</ref> some of them bore similarities to the truck attack on the Christmas market in Berlin.<ref>See [[2014 Nantes attack]] and [[2016 Nice attack]]</ref>

In March, 32 people were killed by [[2016 Brussels bombings|three coordinated suicide bombings]] in the Belgian capital [[Brussels]]. On 14 July, a Tunisian man [[2016 Nice attack|deliberately drove a truck into crowds]] celebrating [[Bastille Day]] in the French city of [[Nice]], killing 86 people. Four days later, an Afghan asylum seeker [[2016 Würzburg train attack|stabbed five people on a train]] near [[Würzburg]], Germany. On 24 July, a Syrian refugee [[2016 Ansbach bombing|blew himself up outside a music festival]] in the German city of [[Ansbach]], wounding fifteen people. Two days later, Islamists [[2016 Normandy church attack|attacked Christians attending a church service]] in [[Normandy]], killing an elderly priest.<ref name="bbcbackground"/> On 26 November, a 12-year-old Iraqi-German boy [[2016 Ludwigshafen bombing plot|planted a nail bomb]] at a Christmas market in [[Ludwigshafen]], but it failed to detonate.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-38343124 "German-Iraqi boy, 12, 'tried to bomb Christmas market'"]. [[BBC News]]. 16 December 2016. Retrieved 21 December 2016.</ref>

On 21 November the [[United States Department of State]] warned that Americans "should exercise caution at holiday festivals, events, and outdoor markets" throughout Europe. This was in view of the threat from ISIL, [[Al-Qaeda]] and affiliated groups, including self-radicalized extremists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/passports/en/alertswarnings/Europe.html|title=Europe Travel Alert|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/20/world/europe/berlin-attack-christmas-market.html|title=Germany Releases Berlin Attack Suspect as ISIS Claims Involvement|date=20 December 2016|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

==Attack==

===Fatal hijacking===
[[File:Terroranschlag-Berlin-Breitscheidplatz-2016 (2) (31731061626) (square crop).jpg|thumb|View into the Christmas market the day after the attack]]
The vehicle involved, a black [[Scania PRT-range|Scania R 450]] [[semi-trailer truck]],<ref>[http://www.berliner-zeitung.de/berlin/terroranschlag-lkw-rast-in-weihnachtsmarkt-auf-breitscheidplatz-25341200 ''LKW rast in Weihnachtsmarkt auf Breitscheidplatz''.] In: ''[[Berliner Zeitung]]'', 19. Dezember 2016</ref> bore [[vehicle registration plates of Poland|Polish number plates]] and belongs to a Polish delivery company, ''Usługi Transportowe (Transport Services) Ariel Żurawski'', based in [[Sobiemyśl]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.money.pl/gospodarka/wiadomosci/artykul/zurawski-ciezarowka-kierowca-polska-zamach,245,0,2222325.html |title=Zamach w Berlinie. Ariel Żurawski dla WP: Najważniejsze dla mnie to znaleźć mojego kierowcę |first=Sebastian |last=Ogórek |date=19 December 2016 |accessdate=20 December 2016|language=pl}}</ref> The truck was on its return leg to Poland, having started its trip in [[Turin]], Italy,<ref name=":1" /> and was transporting steel beams to a Berlin warehouse<ref name="BBCter">{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-38375555 |title=Berlin lorry deaths: Police say 'probably terrorist attack' |publisher=BBC |date=20 December 2016}}</ref> owned by [[ThyssenKrupp]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/20/police-pore-over-polish-lorry-driver-lukasz-urban-final-hours-berlin-attack|title=Police pore over Polish truck driver's final hours for clues to Berlin attack|last=Kirchgaessner|first=Stephanie|date=20 December 2016|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|issn=0261-3077|access-date=21 December 2016}}</ref>

[[File:2016 Berlin attack route map.svg|thumb|right|Route of the truck<ref name="auto3">{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/fotostrecke/fotostrecke-143633-11.html|title=Angriff in Berlin: Der Tag nach der Katastrophe|author=Spiegel Online staff|work=[[Spiegel Online]]|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20161222001857/http://www.spiegel.de/fotostrecke/angriff-in-berlin-fotostrecke-143633-11.html|archivedate=2016-12-22|accessdate=2016-12-22|language=de}}</ref>]]
The head of the delivery company, Ariel Żurawski, reported that his cousin Łukasz Robert Urban<ref name=":3"/><ref name="DIE WELT 2016 / Drei Ansätze">{{cite web | title=Weihnachtsmarkt-Attacke: In diese drei Ansätze setzt die Polizei ihre Hoffnung | website=[[Die Welt]]| date=21 December 2016 | url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article160482426/In-diese-drei-Ansaetze-setzt-die-Polizei-ihre-Hoffnung.html | language=de | accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> had been driving the truck to Berlin, but that he could not imagine him being responsible for the attack.<ref name=":1" /> Żurawski's company last contacted Urban between 15:00 and 16:00, when Urban reported that he had arrived a day early to the Berlin warehouse and that he had to wait there overnight to unload his truck the following morning.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2016/dec/19/berlin-truck-crash-christmas-market-live |title=Berlin truck crash: 'suspicious person' arrested after nine killed at Christmas market – live |last=Jamieson |first=Amber |date=19 December 2016 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|issn=0261-3077|access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=":3" /> The last photo of Urban still alive was taken at a kebab shop near the ThyssenKrupp warehouse at about 14:00.<ref name=":3" />

The family had been unable to contact Urban since 16:00.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wiadomosci.onet.pl/tylko-w-onecie/atak-terrorystyczny-w-berlinie-ciezarowka-wjechala-w-tlum-na-jarmarku-relacja/8bqhv99 |title=Atak terrorystyczny w Berlinie? Ciężarówka wjechała w tłum na jarmarku |date=19 December 2016 |accessdate=20 December 2016|language=pl}}</ref> Żurawski suspected that the truck had been [[truck hijacking|hijacked]] based on its GPS coordinates,<ref name=":1" /> as well as indications that the truck was being driven erratically.<ref name=":3" /> Żurawski later identified the victim found in the truck as his cousin Urban,<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/12/20/first-victim-of-berlin-christmas-market-terror-attack-named-6335443/|title=Truck driver named as first victim of Berlin Christmas market terror attack|first=Nicole Morley for|last=Metro.co.uk|date=20 December 2016|publisher=}}</ref> the original driver of the semi-trailer.<ref name="ntv">{{cite news |url=http://www.n-tv.de/politik/14-28-Szydlo-kondoliert-der-deutschen-Nation-article19368596.html |date=20 December 2016 |publisher=NTV |language=German |title=Liveticker zu Anschlag auf Berliner Weihnachtsmarkt}}</ref> It is believed that Urban was killed by the perpetrator of the attack.<ref name="ft-2016-12-20">{{cite web |title=Germany faces manhunt after Berlin Christmas attack |date=20 December 2016 |website=[[Financial Times]] |first1=Guy |last1=Chazan |first2=James |last2=Shotter |url=https://www.ft.com/content/b3aa2c86-c695-11e6-9043-7e34c07b46ef |accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>

===Attack on Christmas market===
On 19 December 2016, at 20:02 local time,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.zeit.de/gesellschaft/zeitgeschehen/2016-12/berlin-breitscheidplatz-gedaechtniskirche-weihnachtsmarkt|title=Weihnachtsmarkt : Was wir über den Anschlag in Berlin wissen|last=Biermann|first=Kai|date=20 December 2016|last2=Faigle|first2=Philip|newspaper=Die Zeit|issn=0044-2070|last3=Geisler|first3=Astrid|last4=Müller|first4=Daniel|last5=Musharbash|first5=Yassin|last6=Polke-Majewski|first6=Karsten|last7=Venohr|first7=Sascha|access-date=20 December 2016|language=de}}</ref> the perpetrator drove the stolen truck through a [[Christmas market]] at [[Breitscheidplatz]] in the [[City West]] of [[Berlin]], killing 12 people and injuring 56.<ref name="nyt-20161221">{{cite news | last=Eddy | first=Melissa | title=Germany Seeks Tunisian Tied to Berlin Christmas Market Attack | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=21 December 2016 | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/21/world/europe/berlin-christmas-market-attack.html | accessdate=22 December 2016}}</ref><ref name="EddySmale">{{cite news|first1= Melissa| last1= Eddy |first2= Alison |last2= Smale|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/19/world/europe/berlin-christmas-market-truck-crash.html|title=At Least 12 Dead in Berlin After Truck Crashes into Christmas Market|newspaper=The New York Times|date=19 December 2016}}</ref> The truck came from the direction of Hardenbergstraße, drove about {{Convert|50|m}} through the market, and destroyed several stalls<ref name=rtr>{{cite news| first= Michelle| last= Martin |url=http://reuters.com/article/idUSKBN148287|title=Berlin police assume truck was deliberately driven into Christmas market|agency=Reuters| website= Reuters.com| date=20 December 2016}}</ref> before turning back onto Budapester Straße and coming to a stop level with the  [[Kaiser Wilhelm Memorial Church]].<ref name=guard>{{cite news|first1= Kate |last1= Connolly|first2= Philip |last2= Oltermann|first3= Kevin |last3= Rawlinson|first4= Fran|last4= Lawther |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/19/berlin-truck-crashes-into-christmas-market|title=Berlin: suspect held and 12 dead after truck crashes into market|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=19 December 2016}}</ref> Before entering the Christmas market, the truck had circled Breitscheidplatz once.<ref name="spiegel1" /> 

Several witnesses saw the driver leave the truck and flee towards [[Tiergarten (park)|Tiergarten]]. One witness ran after him.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=https://www.welt.de/vermischtes/article160454887/Mutiger-Zeuge-fuehrt-die-Polizei-zum-Verdaechtigen.html|title=Berlin: Mutiger Zeuge führt Polizei zum Verdächtigen|last=|first=|date=20 December 2016|website=Die Welt|publisher=|access-date=20 December 2016|language=German}}</ref>

Łukasz Urban was found dead in the passenger seat of the truck cab; he had been stabbed and shot<ref name="auto1"/><ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/20/berlin-christmas-market-attack-everything-know-far | title = Berlin Christmas market attack: What we know so far |work = The Daily Telegraph | date = 20 December 2016}}</ref> once in the head<ref name="spiegel1">{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/anschlag-in-berlin-attentaeter-fuhr-einmal-um-den-weihnachtsmarkt-herum-a-1126840.html|title=Berlin: Attentäter fuhr einmal um den Weihnachtsmarkt herum|last=|first=|date=20 December 2016|website=Spiegel Online|publisher=|language=German}}</ref> with a small-caliber firearm.<ref name="ntv" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/us-germany-truck-driver-dead-idUSKBN1490Z3?il=0 |title=One of dead at German Christmas market was shot|agency=Reuters|date=20 December 2016}}</ref> Investigators believe that Urban was still alive when the truck reached Breitscheidplatz and was stabbed because he tried to stop the attack. Reports indicated that he grabbed the steering wheel, forcing the truck to veer left and crash to a stop, and was then shot at the scene of the crash. This act may have saved many lives.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ermittler: Es gab einen Kampf im Lastwagen|url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/anschlag-auf-dem-breitscheidplatz-ermittler-es-gab-einen-kampf-im-lastwagen/19161150.html|publisher=''Tagesspiegel''|accessdate=21 December 2016|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20161221111355/http://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/anschlag-auf-dem-breitscheidplatz-ermittler-es-gab-einen-kampf-im-lastwagen/19161150.html|archivedate=21 December 2016|language=German|date=21 December 2016}}</ref> The weapons are still missing.<ref name=":3"/>

==Investigation==
[[File:2016 Berlin Christmas market truck attack.jpg|thumb|right|The truck involved, surrounded by emergency vehicles]]
The police and public prosecutor are investigating the incident as a [[Terrorism in Germany|terrorist attack]].<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/anschlag-in-berlin-bundesanwaltschaft-geht-von-terroristischem-hintergrund-aus-a-1126797.html|title= Anschlag in Berlin: BKA zeigt sich 'hochalarmiert'| language= de| trans-title= Attack in Berlin: BKA on 'high alert'|work= Der Spiegel}}</ref> The Chancellor of Germany, [[Angela Merkel]] said, "We must assume this was a terrorist attack."<ref>{{cite news |title=Merkel on Berlin Xmas Market Tragedy: 'We must assume this was a terrorist attack' |work= Deutsche Welle |date=20 December 2016 |url= http://www.dw.com/en/merkel-on-berlin-xmas-market-tragedy-we-must-assume-this-was-a-terrorist-attack/a-36839928 |accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref> The German Minister of the Interior, [[Thomas de Maizière]], described the incident as a brutal attack.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/inland/thomas-de-maiziere-anschlag-in-berlin-war-brutales-attentat-14584165.html|title=Todesfahrt von Berlin: De Maizière: „Kein Zweifel mehr an Anschlag“| trans-title= Deadly Drive in Berlin: De Maizière: 'No Doubt Any More About Attack'| language= de| date= 20 December 2016|publisher= ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]''|website=faz.net}}</ref> The U.S. Department of State had previously warned of terrorist attacks on Christmas markets in Europe after ISIL took hold of [[Al-Raqqah|Raqqa]] and [[Mosul]].<ref name="Sanchez 2016">{{cite web | last=Sanchez | first=Raf | title=US warns of 'heightened' risk of terror attacks on Christmas markets in Europe as Isil loses grip on Mosul and Raqqa | website=The Telegraph | date=22 November 2016 | url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/11/22/us-warns-heightened-risk-terror-attacks-christmas-markets-europe/ | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref name="travel.state.gov 2016">{{cite web | title=Europe Travel Alert | website=travel.state.gov | publisher= Bureau of Consular Affairs, US State Department| date=9 September 2016 | url= https://travel.state.gov/content/passports/en/alertswarnings/Europe.html | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref> ISIL claimed responsibility for the attack shortly after the release of a Pakistani suspect who was mistakenly detained.<ref name="auto2">{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/berlin-anschlag-vermutet-mutmasslicher-taeter-naved-b-war-offenbar-polizeibekannt-a-1126641.html|title= Noch 14 Menschen in Lebensgefahr|trans-title= Still 14 People in Danger| work= [[Der Spiegel]] |place= [[Hamburg]], Germany |publisher=|language=de}}</ref><ref name="GmbH 2016 / ISIS">{{cite news | work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung (FAZ.net)| title=Nach Anschlag in Berlin: IS reklamiert Attacke auf Weihnachtsmarkt für sich| trans-title= After attack in Berlin: IS reclaims attack on Christmas market for itself | date=20 December 2016 | url= http://www.faz.net/1.4585337 | language=de | place= Frankfurt, Germany| accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref> 

===Suspects===

====Initial suspect====
[[File:Berlin, Breitscheidplatz (2016)-01.jpg|thumb|right|[[Breitscheidplatz]] after the attack]]

On the evening of 19 December, police arrested a suspect, believed to have driven the truck during the attack, near the [[Berlin Victory Column]].<ref name="DIE WELT 2016 / Drei Ansätze" /><ref>{{cite web | title=Berlin truck driver reportedly a refugee from Pakistan or Afghanistan | website=Washington Times | date=19 December 2016 | url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/dec/19/berlin-truck-driver-was-refugee-pakistan-report/ | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.com/en/pakistani-and-afghan-refugees-fear-backlash-after-berlin-attack/a-36843958|title=Pakistani and Afghan refugees fear backlash after Berlin attack|work=DW|date=20 December 2016|accessdate=21 December 2016|first=Shamil|last=Shams}}</ref><ref name="EddySmale"/><ref name=":0" /> He had aroused suspicion by running away from the scene of the attack out of fear that he would be considered a suspect.<ref name="naved">{{cite news|last1=Jamieson|first1=Amber|last2=Lyons|first2=Kate|last3=Topping|first3=Alexandra|last4=Weaver|first4=Matthew|title=Berlin truck attack: first suspect released as driver thought to still be at large – as it happened|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2016/dec/20/berlin-christmas-market-attack-suspect-pakistan-live-coverage|accessdate=22 December 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 December 2016}}</ref> The arrested man denied involvement, and was later identified as a 23-year-old asylum seeker from [[Turbat]], Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-38379157|title=Berlin attack: No certainty over man arrested by police|date=20 December 2016|work=BBC}}</ref> The [[Special Deployment Commando]] of Berlin stormed the hangar at [[Tempelhof]] which is used as a refugee camp, where the arrested man lived with six others in a room. His mobile phone was seized and analyzed. Police sources later suggested that they might have arrested "the wrong man" because the individual in custody did not carry [[gunshot residue]] or any marks that would indicate that he had been in a fight.<ref name="Spiegel"/> Furthermore, forensic tests could not prove that the suspect was inside the cab of the truck.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1303453/germany-releases-pakistani-held-over-berlin-attack|title=Germany releases Pakistani held over Berlin attack|work=Dawn|date=21 December 2016|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> Police therefore believed that the attacker might still be at large.<ref name="Spiegel">{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/anschlag-in-berlin-polizei-zweifelt-an-taeterschaft-des-festgenommenen-a-1126778.html|title=Anschlag in Berlin: Polizei zweifelt an Täterschaft des Festgenommenen|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|language=de}}</ref>
[[Public Prosecutor General (Germany)|German Public Prosecutor General]] Peter Frank said, "We have to get used to the idea that the man apprehended may not be the perpetrator or belong to the group of perpetrators."<ref name="die.zeit.wohl-falsch">{{cite web |url=http://www.zeit.de/gesellschaft/zeitgeschehen/2016-12/berlin-weihnachtsmarkt-kurfuerstendamm-gedaechtniskirche-attentat |title=Berlin: Die Berliner Polizei hat wohl den Falschen | first1= Karin| last1= Geil| first2= Angelika| last2= Finkenwirth| first3= Jakob| last3= Pontius| first4= Sybille| last4=Klormann |date=20 December 2016 |work=Die Zeit|language=de}}</ref><ref name="die.zeit.was-wir-wissen.english">{{cite web |url=http://www.zeit.de/gesellschaft/zeitgeschehen/2016-12/berlin-breitscheidplatz-gedaechtniskirche-weihnachtsmarkt#english-version |title=Weihnachtsmarkt: What we know for sure |last1=Biermann |first1=Kai |last2=Faigle |first2=Philip |last3=Geisler |first3=Astrid |last4=Müller |first4=Daniel |last5=Musharbash |first5=Yassin |last6=Polke-Majewski |first6=Karsten |last7=Venohr |first7=Sascha |translator=Charles Hawley, Daryl Lindsey |date=20 December 2016 |work=Die Zeit}}</ref> The man was released on the evening of 20 December due to the lack of evidence.<ref name="GmbH 2016 / Berlin">{{cite web |work= Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung (FAZ.net)| title=Nach Anschlag in Berlin: Vorläufig Festgenommener ist wieder frei |trans-title= After the Attack in Berlin... | date=20 December 2016 | url=http://www.faz.net/1.4585157 | language=de | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref name="BBC38385961">{{cite news |title= Berlin market attack suspect released |publisher=BBC News |date=20 December 2016 |url=http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-38385961 }}</ref>

====Anis Amri====
[[File:16-12-22-Bundeskriminalamt-Anis-Amri-4.jpg|thumb|Search poster]]
On 21 December, police announced that investigators had found, under the truck's driver's seat, a suspension of deportation permit<!-- Duldungsschreiben "tolerance permit" --><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article160489493/Das-ist-ueber-den-neuen-Tatverdaechtigen-bekannt.html|title=Anschlag in Berlin: Das ist über den neuen Tatverdächtigen bekannt - Welt|publisher=|language=de}}</ref> belonging to Anis Amri, a man who was born in [[Tataouine]], Tunisia, in 1992. Authorities began a Europe-wide search for Amri.<ref name="nyt-20161221"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Nach Berlin-Anschlag: Polizei fahndet bundesweit nach Verdächtigem|url=http://www.tagesschau.de/eilmeldung/eilmeldung-2221.html|publisher=[[Tagesschau (Germany)|Tagesschau]] |accessdate=21 December 2016 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20161221101143/http://www.tagesschau.de/eilmeldung/eilmeldung-2221.html|archivedate=21 December 2016 |language=German |date=21 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Polizei sucht tatverdächtigen Tunesier |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/anschlag-in-berlin-polizei-sucht-tunesier-a-1126931-amp.html|publisher=Spiegel Online |accessdate=21 December 2016|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20161221105918/http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/anschlag-in-berlin-polizei-sucht-tunesier-a-1126931-amp.html|archivedate=21 December 2016|language=German|date=21 December 2016}}</ref> According to investigators, Amri entered Germany from Italy in 2015 and belonged to a [[Salafi movement|Salafist]] network, the so-called "[[True Religion (Islamist organization)|True Religion]]" group, which had grown around the recently-arrested [[Abu Walaa]], a known ISIL recruiter in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|title=Polizei fahndet nach Tunesier Anis A.|url=http://www.tagesschau.de/inland/suche-tatverdaechtiger-103.html|publisher=[[Tagesschau (Germany)|Tagesschau]]|accessdate=21 December 2016 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20161221124035/http://www.tagesschau.de/inland/suche-tatverdaechtiger-103.html|archivedate=21 December 2016|language=German|date=21 December 2016}}</ref> Amri was sought by the [[Federal Criminal Police Office (Germany)|Federal Criminal Police Office]]. Officials called for a public manhunt, issuing a recent picture, and offering a reward of [[Euro|€]]100,000, warning that Amri might be armed and dangerous. He was described as being {{height|cm=178}} tall, weighing approximately {{convert|75|kg|lb}}, with dark hair and brown eyes.<ref name="GmbH 2016 / manhunt">{{cite web | last=GmbH | first=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung | title=Nach Attentat in Berlin: Öffentliche Fahndung nach verdächtigem Tunesier | website=FAZ.NET | date=21 December 2016 | url=http://www.faz.net/1.4586660 | language=de | accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>

Amri arrived for the first time in Europe in 2011 on a refugee raft<ref>{{cite news|title=Chi è Anis Amri, il sospettato della strage di Berlino arrivato a Lampedusa su un barcone|url=http://www.lavocedeltrentino.it/2016/12/22/chi-e-anis-amri-il-sospettato-della-strage-di-berlino-arrivato-a-lampedusa-su-un-barcone/|accessdate=22 December 2016|work=La Voce del Trentino|date=22 December 2016|language=Italian}}</ref> at the island of [[Lampedusa]]. He lied about his age, pretending to be a [[minor (law)|minor]], and was sent to the [[Lampedusa immigrant reception center|temporary migrants reception center]] on the island.<ref name="Paravicini">Guulia Paravicini, [http://www.politico.eu/article/suspected-berlin-attacker-spent-4-years-in-italian-jails/ Suspected Berlin attacker spent 4 years in Italian jails], ''Politico.eu'' (December 22, 2016).</ref> At the center, according to Italian security officials, Amri "took part in a particularly violent riot, when the center was set on fire and several people were injured" and was sentenced for it and robbery<ref name="rawstory.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.rawstory.com/2016/12/berlin-suspect-anis-amri-radicalized-in-italy-jail-father/|title=Berlin suspect Anis Amri ‘radicalized in Italy jail:’ Father|publisher=}}</ref> to four years in prison, which he served in two jails in [[Sicily]].<ref name="Paravicini"/> Amri was released in 2015; according to Italian officials, the Tunisian authorities refused to accept his repatriation to Tunisia, and it is believed that he went to Germany around this time.<ref name="Paravicini"/>

In Tunisia, Amri was sentenced ''[[Trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' to five years in prison, "reportedly for aggravated theft with violence".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-12-21/suspect-in-berlin-attack-is-just-the-latest-tunisian-jihadi|title=Suspect in Deadly Berlin Attack Is Latest Tunisian Jihadi|date=21 December 2016|publisher=|accessdate=23 December 2016|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-38399561 Berlin attack: Tunisian fugitive 'had been under surveillance'], BBC News (December 22, 2016).</ref> Prior to that he was arrested several times over drug use and possession.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/20/berlin-market-attack-suspect-named-23-year-old-asylum-seeker/ |title=Berlin terror attack: Tunisian suspect was investigated over earlier terror plotÂ |publisher=Telegraph.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-12-22}}</ref> According to his family, he drank alcohol, took drugs and was initially not religious, but had been radicalized in Italian jails.<ref name="rawstory.com"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.reuters.com/article/us-germany-truck-suspect-idUSKBN14B1XU | title=Berlin attack suspect emerged from jail with 'totally different mentality' | via=Reuters | date=December 22, 2016 | accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> The man arrived in Germany in July 2015 and applied for asylum in April 2016. He has used at least six different aliases and also posed as a citizen of Syria, Egypt and Lebanon. He reportedly had tried to recruit participants for a terrorist attack since the spring and once tried to buy a pistol from an undercover police officer. He had been overheard, by the German intelligence, offering to carry out a suicide attack, but the German authorities had decided to not arrest him because they deemed him a mere ''errand boy''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/12/22/berlin-terror-attack-tunisian-suspect-anis-amri-investigated/|title=Berlin terror attack: dashcam video shows truck speeding into Christmas market|publisher=}}</ref> In Germany he was involved in a bar brawl and drug dealing, later he was involved in a knife attack over drugs in July 2016 and disappeared after police tried to question him.<ref name="suspect">{{cite web|last1=Connolly|first1=Kate|title=market attack Berlin attack suspect Anis Amri had been on watchlist since January |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/21/berlin-attack-suspect-anis-amri-under-monitoring-since-january?CMP=twt_a-world_b-gdnworld |website=theguardian.com|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>

On 23 December, around 03:00 [[Central European Time|CET]], Amri was killed in a shootout with police at [[Sesto San Giovanni railway station]], near [[Milan]], [[Italy]]. The suspect had just arrived by train from [[Chambéry]], France, and fired at police officers after they had asked him for documents at a routine control.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bonini|first1=Carlo|last2=Pisa|first2=Massimo|title=L'attentatore di Berlino Anis Amri ucciso a Sesto: ha urlato "Allah Akbar"|url=http://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2016/12/23/news/sparatoria_sesto_san_giovanni-154711759/|accessdate=23 December 2016|agency=repubblica.it|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-38415287|title=Berlin attack suspect Anis Amri killed in Milan|date=23 December 2016|publisher=|accessdate=23 December 2016|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The [[Italian Minister of the Interior]], Marco Minniti, stated that a policeman had been hospitalized with a shoulder injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/anschlag-in-berlin/innenminister-bestaetigt-amri-in-italien-erschossen-14589001.html |title=Innenminister bestätigt: Amri in Italien erschossen |publisher=Faz.net |date= |accessdate=2016-12-23|language =de}}</ref>

